## Why This Is Asked
Edge on-device summarization blends ML, privacy, and cost; tests ownability of hardware bounds, latency budgets, and regulatory implications, plus clear go/no-go and break-even criteria.

## Key Concepts
- On-device ML constraints (model size, quantization, memory)
- Energy/latency budgets and measurement
- Rollout strategy across platforms
- Compliance and telemetry design

## Code Example
```javascript
// mock harness: measure energy and latency for a given token batch size
function evaluateBatch(tokens) {
  // simulate on-device inference metrics
  const latencyMs = Math.max(30, Math.min(120, tokens.length * 0.6));
  const energyJ = latencyMs * 0.01;
  return { latencyMs, energyJ };
}
``` 

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you validate model drift offline?
- How would you compare with a server-assisted approach?

## Why This Is Asked

Gauges ability to justify product bets with a pragmatic, numbers-driven approach and to handle uncertainty in inputs.

## Key Concepts

- Cost estimation
- Benefit estimation
- Break-even analysis
- Reasonable assumptions

## Code Example

```javascript
// Simple CBA calculator
function cba(params) {
  const {maU, lift, arpu, months, cost} = params;
  const annualizedBenefit = maU * lift * arpu * months;
  return {annualizedBenefit, cost, breakevenMonths: cost / (annualizedBenefit || 1)};
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adjust if MAU grows or adoption changes?
- What if ARPU uplift is not uniform across user segments?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a privacy-preserving, on-device ML feature with a clear financial rationale and real-world constraints.

## Key Concepts

- On-device ML size/latency trade-offs
- Energy, memory, and storage budgeting for mobile apps
- Telemetry costs and delta-based model updates
- Regulatory/compliance costs and risk assessment
- Go/no-go criteria and break-even planning

## Code Example

```javascript
function inferLeadScore(features, model) {
  // simple LR-like dot product
  let score = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < features.length; i++) {
    score += features[i] * model.weights[i];
  }
  return 1 / (1 + Math.exp(-score));
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you validate drift and schedule model updates offline?
- How would you audit privacy, regulatory compliance, and data minimization during rollout?

